[[File:Anne Eidemiller Rudloe.jpg|thumb|Picture of Anne Eidemiller Rudloe at the U.S. Naval base in Panama City in the underwater research and diving techniques as part of the "Scientists in the Sea" program.]]

'''Anne Rudloe''' (n<U+00E9>e '''Anne Eidemiller''', December 24, 1947 - April 27, 2012) was a US marine biologist. She was the co-founder of the [[Gulf Specimen Marine Laboratory]] in [[Panacea, Florida]].

==Biography==
Rudloe was born Anne Eidemiller, December 24, 1947 in [[Troy, Ohio]] and grew up in [[Hampton, Virginia]]. In 1971, she married writer and naturalist Jack Rudloe.

She earned a BSc (Biology) at [[Mary Washington College]] in 1969, and MSc (Oceanography) in 1972 and PhD (Marine Biology) in 1978 under William F Hernkind at [[Florida State University]]. She trained at the U.S. Naval base in Panama City in underwater research and diving techniques in the "Scientists in the Sea" program. She was an FSU adjunct professor of biological science.  She co-founded the [[Gulf Specimen Marine Laboratory]], of which she was the managing director.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Blaustein|first=Richard J.|year=2008|title=Biodiversity Hotspot: The Florida Panhandle|journal=[[BioScience]]|volume=58|issue=9|pages=784<U+2013>90|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/10.1641/B580904}}</ref>

Rudloe published four books, in addition to scientific articles on [[horseshoe crabs]], [[electric rays]], [[mysid shrimp]], and [[sea turtles]]. She wrote for a larger audience as well, in publications such as ''[[National Geographic]]'' and ''[[Smithsonian Magazine]]''; the article "Trouble in Bayou Country" (''National Geographic'' 182 (September 1979): 377-9), which she co-wrote with her husband, is frequently cited in accounts of environmental damage to the [[Atchafalaya Basin]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Reuss|first=Martin|year=1982|title=The Army Corps of Engineers and Flood-Control: Politics on the Lower Mississippi|journal=[[Louisiana History]]|publisher=[[Louisiana Historical Association]]|volume=23|issue=2|pages=131<U+2013>48|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/4232166}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Colten|first=Craig E.|year=2002|title=Reintroducing Nature to the City: Wetlands in New Orleans|journal=[[Environmental History]]|volume=7|issue=2|pages=226<U+2013>46|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/3985683}}</ref> Rudloe was posthumously honored with the 2014 Education and Outreach Environmental Law Institute National Wetlands Award<ref>[http://www.elinwa.org/2014-national-wetlands-awards-winners#Anne 2014 Education and Outreach] National Wetlands Awards Winners, Environmental Law Institute (ELI), Washington DC, Retrieved January 30, 2015</ref>. Rudloe also studied Zen Bhuddism and received INGA ([[Dharma transmission]]) to teach as a JDPSN (Jido Pope Sanim) in the Kwan Um School of [[Zen]]. She then became the Abbot at the Cypress Tree Zen Center in Tallahassee, FL. She was a frequent guest contributor for National Public Radio for both her conservation efforts and Zen Bhuddism. She died of [[colon cancer]], April 27, 2012.<ref>[http://www.thewakullanews.com/content/anne-rudloe-obituary Anne Rudloe Obituary] Wakulla News Wednesday, May 2, 2012, retrieved Feb 20, 2015</ref><ref>Orser, F [http://www.library.ufl.edu/spec/manuscript/guides/rudloe.htm A Guide to the Jack and Anne Rudloe Papers] University of Florida Smathers Libraries, Special and Area Studies Collections, September 2011 retrieved February 20, 2015</ref><ref>[http://www.mocavo.com/Mwc-Today-1983-Spring-Volume-8/955480/7 Alumna Writes, Lives, Researches Florida Ecology] Mocavo Records, MWC Today, 1983 (Spring), pg7-8, retrieved February 20, 2015</ref><ref name = "FSU Research Review">Bettendorf, Elizabeth. [http://rinr.fsu.edu/issues/2009summer/_doc/rinrsummer2009.pdf "A place, a purpose, a Panacea"] Florida State University Research Review, Summer 2009, p28-39</ref><ref>"Jack and Anne Rudloe reach millions to save Florida wetlands" Wetlands Warriors pg 2, 2005</ref>

==Selected works==
*''Butterflies on the Sea Wind'' (2002)
*''Priceless Florida'' (2004, with E. Whitney and D.B. Means)
*''The Endless Quest for Pink Gold'' (2010, with Jack Rudloe)
*''Zen in a Wild Country'' (2012)

